  "local_port": 47698,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you use Roku to browse the internet?",
  "response": "Roku devices do not come with a built-in web browser, making direct browsing of the internet somewhat limited. However, there are a few ways to access web content on your Roku. Here are some methods you can use to browse the internet on a Roku device:\n\n1. **Screen Mirroring**: \n   - If you have a smartphone or tablet, you can use screen mirroring to display your device\u2019s screen on your Roku. This allows you to use your device\u2019s web browser.\n   - To enable screen mirroring, go to your Roku\u2019s settings, select \"System,\" then \"Screen mirroring,\" and choose your preferred mode.\n   - On an Android device, swipe down from the top of the screen to access quick settings and select \"Cast.\" For iOS devices, you can use AirPlay to mirror your screen.\n\n2. **Roku Web Browser Channel**: \n   - Some unofficial channels or apps may provide basic web browsing capabilities. Look for channels like \"Web Browser X\" in the Roku Channel Store. Keep in mind that these channels may have limited functionality and performance.\n\n3. **Using Streaming Apps**: \n   - You can access many websites that have corresponding apps on Roku, such as YouTube, Netflix, and Hulu. You can find and download these apps directly from the Roku Channel Store.\n\n4. **Roku TV with Built-in Browser**:\n   - Some Roku TVs may have a built-in web browser. If your Roku TV has this feature, you can access it from the apps menu.\n\n5. **Casting from a Computer**: \n   - If you want to display your computer's browser on your Roku, you can use the \"Cast\" feature available in Google Chrome. Ensure your device is connected to the same network as your Roku, and then choose \"Cast\" from the Chrome menu to display your browser on your TV.\n\nUsing these methods, you can browse the internet indirectly while enjoying your Roku device.",
